Introduction¶

Inspired by the recent ship event at Baltimore Harbor, our group is interested in seeing how shipping of auto parts in the Baltimore Harbor affects the sale of vehicles. As most vehicles sold on the east coast come through the Baltimore Harbor, it would be interesting to see the link between imported car parts and the fluctuation in car sales. In addition, seeing how various regions in the US are impacted by the port trade at the harbor can give us insight into the price, location, and spread of vehicles throughout the mainland. Investigating such related trends is important as it can provide insight into the impact of inflation on car prices versus the actual supply and demand of parts.

Data Collection¶

At this stage of our project, we will be looking for datasets related to our topic of car sales and the number of cars going through the Baltimore Harbor. For a topic such as this, we needed to find a detailed dataset that had information spanning years with numerous other features. Naturally, we turned to Kaggle and found a dataset on Vehicle Sales (car_prices.csv). This dataset has data on vehicular sales from 1982 to 2015, with a heavy emphasis on sales made between 2012 and 2015. In addition, it has sales data regarding in which state and at what date each car was sold.

In order to link the Vehicle Sales data to our claim, we needed to find a dataset on imports coming through the Baltimore Harbor. We were able to find a dataset for this on the Maryland Open Data Portal (Maryland_Port_Administration_General_Cargo_20240609.csv), with information on Auto Tons (tons of automobiles and automobile parts) and Ron/Roff tons (tons of automobiles). Furthermore, the Maryland port data had information dating back to 1998 until last month.

However, these datasets didnt have all the information we needed as there were information gaps in total vehicular sales to match with the Maryland Port Data. Since the initial Vehicular Sales data didnt have enough information before 2012, we used a total vehicular sales dataset from the Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis (TOTALSA.csv) to gather data on total vehicle sales per month ranging from the 1980s to the 2020s. To match with the Maryland Port Data and the Kaggle Vehicle Sales data, we made the cutoff from 1998 to 2015, for consistency.

Our last dataset is from the Bureau of Transportation Statistics ("Book(Sheet1).csv"), using their data to obtain more information on New and Used Cars. This dataset will help add additional data that we will use to make conclusions about trends between new cars and imported data from the Baltimore Harbor.

# Function to parse each saledate value into
# year-month-day
def month_year(date):
  parts = date.split()
  month = parts[1]
  day = parts[2]
  year = parts[3]
  return month + ' ' + day + ' ' + year

cpf['saledate'] = cpf['saledate'].apply(month_year)

# Apply a standardized to_datetime to match the other dataframes
cpf['saledate'] = pd.to_datetime(cpf['saledate'], format = '%b %d %Y')

Exploratory Analysis & Data Visualization¶

In this section of the project, we will be visualizing and graphing our data using Matplot and Seaborn libraries. In addition, we will attempt to perform statistical analyses on our data to test our claims and find real-world conclusions based on the results. Essentially, we will be looking to identify trends and affirm our beliefs through the statistical methods in this section.

First Test: Finding a Correlation between Auto Tons into the Baltimore Port and Total Car Sales (from 1998 - 2016)¶

Source: Maryland Port Administration and Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis

For this test, we are looking to check if there is a correlation between the import of auto tons into the Baltimore Harbor and the Total Car Sales across the country. We have plotted two line graphs displaying total vehicle sales and auto tons versus the date. With the comparison of these graphs we can see that when the number of auto tons decreases, total vehicle sales tend to decrease as well. We can see this occur clearly around 2008 (economic recession) on the graph where both values decrease and gradually increase simultaneously. That being said, our null hypothesis is that there is NOT a strong correlation between the number of Auto Tons into the Baltimore Harbor and Total Vehicle Sales across the U.S. Our alternative hypothesis is that there is a STRONG correlation between the number of Auto Tons into the Baltimore Harbor and Total Vehicle Sales across the U.S.

Plotting the Date versus Auto Tons line graph

print(f"Spearman correlation coefficient: {res.statistic:.3f}")

Spearman correlation coefficient: -0.256

Conclusion: In our third graph for this test, we created a scatter plot of the auto tons versus the total vehicle sales. This graph depicted a relationship between the data that was contrary to our beliefs. After running two separate regressions (Linear Reg and Spearman), we found that there indeed was a low correlation between the two variables with an R2 score of 0.014 and a Spearman value of -0.256. These values indicate a weak and almost non-existent relationship between Auto Tons and Total Vehicle Sales. This conclusion of failing to reject the null hypothesis was rather surprising considering the similarity of both the values trends at pivotal points.

Second Test: Comparing Sales Data and Selling Price Based on Region of America¶

West Coast vs. Middle vs. East Coast

For this test, we are comparing selling prices of cars based on the region of America to see if vehicle prices are increasing from east to west. If this is true, then it will affirm our assumption that a majority of cars imported to the U.S. come from the Baltimore Harbor, which is located on the East Coast.

Filtered our car sales data frame to consist of cars that were sold in the mainland U.S. excluding states like Hawaii and Puerto Rico.

Conducting the ANOVA test on all of the regions selling prices

Our null hypothesis is that there is NO significant difference in the mean value of the selling price between the three different regions of car sales data. On the other hand, our alternative hypothesis is that there is a SIGNIFICANT difference in the mean value of the selling price between the three different regions of car sales data.

In [ ]:
import scipy
# Perform the one-way ANOVA
res = scipy.stats.f_oneway(west_coast_sales, east_coast_sales, middle_sales)

# Print the results
print("ANOVA Test Result:")
print(f"P-value: {res.pvalue}")

ANOVA Test Result:
P-value: 4.284099116986088e-146
In [ ]:
from scipy.stats import tukey_hsd

#Perform thee Turkey HSD post-hoc test
res = tukey_hsd(west_coast_sales, east_coast_sales, middle_sales)
print(res)

Tukey's HSD Pairwise Group Comparisons (95.0% Confidence Interval)

 (0 - 1)    860.922     0.000   779.435   942.410

Conclusion: In comparing the three different groups using the ANOVA, we were able to reject our null hypothesis with a p-value of 4.284099116986088e-146, which is close to zero. Considering this, we decided to dig deeper into the data and conduct a post hoc test using the Turkey HSD method in Scipy. In doing so, the test resulted in rejecting the null hypothesis for all inter-group differences, further asserting our alternative hypothesis. By rejecting the null hypothesis, we have concluded that there is a significant increase in vehicle prices moving from the East Coast to the Middle to the West Coast. This can be attributed to our original assumption that a majority of the influx of cars go through the Baltimore port which can be backed up by the difference in the selling price of cars between the East Coast and West Coast.

# Filtering to get rid of missing data
AvgNewCar = AvgNewCar[AvgNewCar['CUUR0000SETA01'] != '.']
AvgUsedCar = AvgUsedCar[AvgUsedCar['CUSR0000SETA02'] != '.']

# functions to return the average price of a new car and used car
def CPItoAverageCost_New(CPI):
  CPI2 = float(CPI)
  avg_price=(CPI2/100)*9000
  return avg_price

def CPItoAverageCost_Used(CPI):
  CPI2 = float(CPI)
  avg_price=(CPI2/100)*5000
  return avg_price

#apply the functionss on the columns to obtain a new car and used car accurate cost
AvgUsedCar['Used'] = AvgUsedCar['CUSR0000SETA02'].apply(CPItoAverageCost_Used)
AvgNewCar['New'] = AvgNewCar['CUUR0000SETA01'].apply(CPItoAverageCost_New)

AvgCar = pd.merge(AvgNewCar, AvgUsedCar, on='DATE')

For the final test, we looked at a comparison between the total amount of new cars and used cars sold throughout the country. From the First Test it is reasonable to hypothesize that with the increase in importing auto parts over the years, new car sales should be equivalent or overtake used car sales. To come to a conclusion on our data we have created a stacked bar chart to show the distribution of used cars and new cars with total sales on a year to year basis. Alongside that, we employed a T-test to see if there is a difference between the means of the total sales of used and new cars.

In [ ]:
from scipy import stats
merged_df['new sales'] = merged_df['new sales'].str.replace(',', '').astype(int)
merged_df['used sales'] = merged_df['used sales'].str.replace(',', '').astype(int)

t_statistic, p_value = stats.ttest_ind(merged_df['new sales'], merged_df['used sales'])

print(f"T-statistic: {t_statistic}")
print(f"P-value: {p_value}")

T-statistic: -34.52724218922556
P-value: 4.664324846060292e-28

Upon inspection we saw a very clear trend favoring used cars in total sales with a t-value of about -34.53 and an extremely small p-value of 4.6^(-28). Comparing this to 0.05 level of significance, this indicates the difference is large and not accidental, showing a consistent and ever present trend in the automotive industry.

Plotting a stacked bar graph to showcase the differences between used car sales and new car sales

Conclusion: The Values for this test show a clear weighted favor for used cars which leads to the question of why imported car numbers continue to rise. A look at the data shows that new car sales are actually steadily rising as used car sales slowly decline. This may help correlate the two trends and make sense of the data. These trends go hand in hand with the increase of total car sales since 2010, which is indicated by a previous graph. Although our hypothesis is proven incorrect until recent, the data suggests that our hypothesis may be correct in the future due to increasing new car sales and decreasing used car sales.

Now we have seen certain trends in the data regarding the relationship between shipping, car price, date, etc. Let's build on these findings via Machine Learning Models to create predictive models to map such relationships in the data.

To begin, let us model the relationship between shipping auto tons and total sales, as it would be interesting to predict the state of the car market based on the shipping data.

Demographics of Car Sales¶

It is evident that the car market across the US is widespread, however, seeing differences in the types of cars purchased would be interesting to see among the different regions of the US.

In [ ]:

Although the data is spread relatively equally throughout the price ranges for each region, we tend to see the West Coast have slightly more expensive cars. We will run a classifier to see if our model can classify the "price bracket" (cheap, middle, or expensive) of a car based on features like make year, saledate, region of the United States, etc.

Note: The code below makes the assumption that a "cheap" car is less than \$10000 and expensive is \$75000 and above.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

print(cpf.columns)
#X = cpf[['saleage', 'sellingprice', 'makeyear']]
cpf["Coast_Num"] = cpf['Coast'].map({'west_coast': 0, 'middle': 1, 'east_coast': 2})
cpf["Price_Bracket"] = cpf["sellingprice"].apply(lambda x: "Cheap" if x < 10000 else ("Middle" if x < 75000 else "Expensive"))
X = cpf[['saleage', 'Coast_Num', 'makeyear']]
y = cpf['Price_Bracket']

# Split the data into training and testing sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2)
clf = DecisionTreeClassifier()

clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)

accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
print("Accuracy:", accuracy)

Index(['makeyear', 'sellingprice', 'saledate', 'mmr', 'state', 'Coast',
       'saleage'],
      dtype='object')
Accuracy: 0.8330374295521382

With the help of the Decision Tree, we see that the features of age, region of US, and make year can help to accurately classify the price range of a car relatively accurately. This indicates that these variables are interrelated and are classifiable via classification models.

Insight & Policy Decision¶

Through our usage of machine learning models and statistical methods, we were able to analyze Maryland Port Data and car sales over two decades of data. Through our investigation, we can conclude a negligible relation between auto sales and Maryland Port Data. This conclusion does not lead us to believe there is a correlation between the two variables but instead that there are unseen variables that could have a greater correlation. On the other hand, using an ANOVA test, we can conclude that there is a statistical significance in the prices increasing from the east coast to the west coast. We believe that this is due to the shipping costs that incur as vehicles are transported over mainland America. Overall, we believe that this topic requires further research and more data to be able to conduct more tests and obtain different conclusions. Considering the recent bridge collapse in Baltimore, we would need more time and data to fully explore some of the ramifications that it caused not only on the East Coast but also on the west coast as well.
